explanation:
Why each symbol is required for determining whether OS_rmdir contains dead code:

- OS_TranslatePath
  - The function is invoked by OS_rmdir and determines the control flow (return_code) and may have side-effects (e.g., modify local_path, register test stubs, produce logging). You must know its semantics: possible return values, whether it always returns a fixed code, whether it always mutates local_path even on failure, and any side-effects that would make the call necessary. This decides if the call (or some of its internal operations) is removable without changing program behaviour.

- OS_DirRemove_Impl
  - The call guarded by the OS_SUCCESS test; to judge whether the conditional call is necessary, you must know what OS_DirRemove_Impl does (side-effects, global state changes) and whether calling it (or omitting it) would affect program behaviour. If OS_DirRemove_Impl is a no-op in some builds, that could make the conditional call dead.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The symbolic return-code constant used in the conditional. Its exact value and definition (and any build-dependent mapping of success/failure codes) are required to determine whether the if-condition is meaningful or always/never true (which would make the guarded call or the test redundant).

- OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN
  - Defines the size of local_path. While not directly a control-flow symbol, its definition matters for whether the buffer is actually used safely (e.g., if too small causing truncation) and whether the local buffer allocation is necessary. If local_path is never effectively used (e.g., OS_TranslatePath never writes it), the buffer allocation could be considered dead.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr
  - These unit-test / stub framework symbols appear in the static call graph reachable from OS_rmdir (through the implementation of OS_TranslatePath or OS_DirRemove_Impl). They can introduce side-effects (registration, handlers, or test-only behaviour) that are executed when OS_rmdir is called. To decide whether any operation in OS_rmdir (or its immediate callees) is dead you must know whether these stub-framework calls are invoked as part of normal operation or only in test builds, and whether their execution affects program behaviour. If they are invoked unconditionally and have observable effects, removing the parent calls would change behaviour; if they are no-ops in production builds, parts of the call chain might be dead in those builds.

Notes: The above set focuses on the immediate callees/constants and the unit-test hooks that the static graph shows reachable from OS_rmdir. Knowing the precise implementations and build-config variants of these symbols is necessary to conclude whether any executed operation in the OS_rmdir call sequence is removable without affecting program behaviour (i.e., constitutes dead code).
